The patient, a 30-year-old woman, presents with a 3-year history of infertility, despite her husband having normal sperm counts. Additionally, she experiences episodic pelvic and back pain, accompanied by painful diarrhea, which occurs about once a month and lasts for 4-6 days. These symptoms, along with the fact that she has regular menstrual cycles and a normal hysterosalpingogram, suggest that her infertility and symptoms may be related to a condition affecting her reproductive system.

Given her symptoms of pelvic and back pain, painful diarrhea, and infertility, the most likely underlying mechanism is the presence of endometrial tissue outside the uterine cavity, which is characteristic of endometriosis. Endometriosis can cause inflammation, scarring, and adhesions in the pelvic area, leading to pain, infertility, and other symptoms. The fact that her symptoms occur around the time of her menstrual cycle further supports this diagnosis.

